             <div id="story">
                <h2 class="title">Editing your digital images without the mystery, Part III: compositing</h2>
        <div class="byline"><span class="author">By <a href="/author/dave-girard/">Dave Girard</a></span> | <span class="posted">Last updated <abbr class="timeago datetime" title="2006-01-30T0:55:00Z">January 29, 2006 6:55 PM</abbr></span></div>
        
      


              <div id="" class="body" style="">          
        <!--body--><!--page 1--><h2>Introduction</h2><div class="ImageLeft" style="border: 1px dotted gray">
<p align="left">
<span class="ImageCaption"><strong>The series:</strong></span>
<br />
<a href="/guides/tweaks/mystery.ars">Part I: Levels, curves, and noise</a><br />
<a href="/guides/tweaks/mystery-2.ars">Part II: Retouching techniques 101</a>
<br />
<font color="grey">Part III: Compositing</font>
</p>
</div>
<p>
Welcome to the third and final installation of the Ars Digital Imaging workshop. In this last one, we&#39;ll be getting into the hardest part of digital imaging: compositing. &quot;Composite&quot; is just a ten-dollar word for a combination of images and here we&#39;ll be covering how to combine one or more photos for convincing results. If you&#39;re brand new to digital imaging and don&#39;t know say, the definition of &quot;digital&quot; or &quot;imaging,&quot; then I suggest a little more reading on the subject before jumping head first into this tutorial. It&#39;s written assuming you&#39;ve got a basic understanding of level adjustments, curves, selection by color, feathering and layer masks since that&#39;s what we covered in the first two articles <a href="/guides/tweaks/mystery.ars">here</a> and <a href="/guides/tweaks/mystery-2.ars">here</a>.
</p>
<p>
In keeping with the previous articles, I&#39;ll do my best to keep these application agnostic and show examples from The GIMP, a very competent image editor but there are certain things which will require slight workarounds for GIMP users. For the most part, these differences are easily overcome with a little hunting around in the interface, like for instance with the Offset filter I mentioned in the second tutorial. In The GIMP it&#39;s in Layer/Transform/Offset in the Layer menu. Thanks to Andrew Pieter Van Pernis for that tip and let me say how happy I am for the sake of his childhood that he has that R in his last name.
</p>
<p>
But before we start with the actual editing, let&#39;s talk about layer masks again since I could see some of the students started looking in their desk like I was going to ask them to explain what they were when I mentioned them. I&#39;ve used masking a few times in these tutorials to accomplish different things and understanding how masks work is essential to good compositing. To paraphrase the previous articles, masks are like stencils in that they let your image layer through, with the black areas indicating hidden masked areas and the white areas indicating full opacity:
</p>
<div class="CenteredImage">
<img src="http://media.arstechnica.com/images/articles/compositing/p1_mask_show_again.jpg" />
</div>
<p>
The most crucial difference between a simple stencil and a layer mask is that layer masks can have many levels of transparency. To illustrate, see how a stack of two simple layers looks without any masking: 
</p>
<div class="CenteredImage">
<img src="http://media.arstechnica.com/images/articles/compositing/mask1.jpg" />
</div>
<p>
The pink layer is completely obscured by the blue layer. Once we add a layer mask (Layer/Layer Mask/Reveal All) and put a gradient in the mask channel, it ends up looking like this:
</p>
<div class="CenteredImage">
<img src="http://media.arstechnica.com/images/articles/compositing/mask1-2.jpg" />
</div>
<p>
The final composite looks like a gradient between blue and pink but the mask is simply doing all the work on the blue layer, going progressively from 100% hidden (black) and 100% opaque (white) with the transition of gray being what creates the blend. These gray transitions are the key to convincing blending between two images. In this motion blurred 3-D rendering, you can see that making a selection of the black areas to make them transparent is not a simple task: 
</p>
<div class="CenteredImage">
<img src="http://media.arstechnica.com/images/articles/compositing/motionblurtest.jpg" />
</div>
<p>
Since the blur isn&#39;t consistent, you can&#39;t just draw a simple selection around the object and feather it:
</p>
<div class="CenteredImage">
<img src="http://media.arstechnica.com/images/articles/compositing/masking_bad2.jpg" />
</div>
<p>
You&#39;re losing all of the motion and still have a black halo. This is why 3-D packages typically render an alpha channel with the image to use as a transparency mask in compositing programs like After Effects or Shake, so you aren&#39;t left to your own devices to get the objects to blend. Unfortunately photographs don&#39;t come with alpha channels so it&#39;s up to you to build your own, working up the blends in different areas to match the focus, motion blur, grain, etc. This is where you spend most of your time in compositing. But there are many ways of making the work easier on yourself and a lot of that has to do with selection.
</p>


        
        
                
        </div>
        
        
       
